[Student "S"]
{You respond with your 5-card Major, 1\S.

Partner jumps to 3\H.  

With partner's 16-18 points you probably have enough strength for game.

With partner's six \Hs you have an 8-card fit.

So you bid 4\H.

East would play 4\H.

Click 

West plays 4\H. North leads \CA, \CK, \C4. South plays \C8 then \C2.

<b>West plays 4\H. North leads \CA, \CK, \C4. South plays \C8 then \C2.</b>

Losers: \S 0 : \H 0 : \D 1 : \C 3 : Total = 4

Suppose you discard a \D from dummy. If South doesn't ruff this \Cthen your \CQ will win. You could then try to establish dummy's \DQ to discard your fourth \C on. 

But you know that plan won't work because South <b>IS</b> going to ruff this \C if you discard. You only have one chance to make this contract, and that is the chance that South was not dealt the \HJ. So you ruff with dummy's \H10 and pray South doesn't over-ruff.

The prayer was answered, South did not hold the \HJ. 

So you won that trick and still had your \CQ to use after you pulled trumps.}
[Play "W"]CA

